var definitions = ['<h2>Sie spielen mit einem Hund.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the third-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "they" in English, or the formal second-person singular pronoun, equivalent to "you". Here, it’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>spielen</strong> This is the present tense form of the verb "spielen", which means "to play". It describes the action that the subject is performing.</div><div><strong>mit</strong> This is a preposition in German that means "with". It is used here to introduce the object of the sentence, indicating the company in which the action is being performed.</div><div><strong>einem</strong> This is the indefinite article in the dative case for masculine and neuter nouns in German. It translates to "a" or "an" in English and is used here because the preposition "mit" requires the dative case.</div><div><strong>Hund</strong> This is a masculine noun in German meaning "dog". It is the object of the preposition "mit" and the entity with which the subject is playing.</div>','<h2>Er will mit dir ins Büro gehen.</h2><div><strong>Er</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "he" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>will</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the modal verb "wollen", which means "to want to" or "to intend to". In this sentence, it expresses the subject’s desire or intention.</div><div><strong>mit</strong> This is a German preposition meaning "with". It indicates the companionship or association in the action described by the verb.</div><div><strong>dir</strong> This is the second-person singular dative pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s used here to indicate the person with whom the subject wants to perform the action.</div><div><strong>ins</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "in" (meaning "into" or "to") and the definite article "das" (neuter singular), which together often translate to "into the" or "to the" in English. Here, it’s used before the noun "Büro", indicating movement towards the office.</div><div><strong>Büro</strong> This is a German noun meaning "office". It’s the location the subject wants to go to, combined with the preposition-article contraction "ins", it becomes "into the office".</div><div><strong>gehen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the German verb "gehen", which means "to go". In this sentence, it describes the action that "Er" wishes to take, connected by the modal verb "will".</div>','<h2>Er schreibt mit seiner linken Hand.</h2><div><strong>Er</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "he" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>schreibt</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "schreiben", which means "to write". It indicates the action that the subject is performing.</div><div><strong>mit</strong> This is a preposition in German that can be translated to "with" in English. It’s used here to introduce the means or instrument with which the action of the verb is being performed.</div><div><strong>seiner</strong> This is the possessive pronoun in the masculine singular dative form that corresponds to "his" in English. It shows possession, indicating that the hand belongs to the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>linken</strong> This is an adjective in German meaning "left". The adjective is inflected to match the gender, case, and number of the noun it describes, here reflecting the dative masculine singular due to the preceding possessive pronoun and dative preposition "mit".</div><div><strong>Hand</strong> This is a feminine singular noun in German, meaning "hand". It serves as the object of the preposition "mit" and is in the dative case due to the influence of the preposition.</div>','<h2>Sie lernen seit Januar Deutsch.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the third-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "they" in English. However, it can also be the formal second-person singular pronoun, equivalent to the formal "you" in English. The context of the sentence is needed to determine which one it is.</div><div><strong>lernen</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "lernen", which means "to learn". If "Sie" is being used in the formal second-person singular, "lernen" would still be the correct form of the verb.</div><div><strong>seit</strong> This is a preposition meaning "since" in English. It indicates the starting point of an activity or condition that continues up to the present.</div><div><strong>Januar</strong> This is the German word for "January". It’s a noun and it’s in the dative case after the preposition "seit".</div><div><strong>Deutsch</strong> This is the German word for "German", referring to the language. In this sentence, it is the direct object of the verb "lernen" and is in the accusative case.</div>','<h2>Seit wann wohnen Sie in Deutschland?</h2><div><strong>Seit</strong> This is a German preposition that translates to "since" in English. It indicates the starting point of a period of time.</div><div><strong>wann</strong> This is the German word for "when". Combined with "seit", it forms a common phrase structure asking for the starting point of an event or action.</div><div><strong>wohnen</strong> This is the German verb for "to live" or "to reside". It is in the present tense and indicates the action of inhabiting or dwelling in a place.</div><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the formal second-person singular or plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s capitalized here because it is the formal address for politeness, and it is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>in</strong> This is a German preposition that means "in", indicating the location where the action of the verb "wohnen" takes place.</div><div><strong>Deutschland</strong> This is the German noun for "Germany". It is the name of the country and is used here to indicate the location where the person being addressed resides.</div>','<h2>Seit zweitausenddreizehn wohnen wir hier.</h2><div><strong>Seit</strong> This is a German preposition that means "since". It is used here to indicate the starting point of a period of time.</div><div><strong>zweitausenddreizehn</strong> This is the German word for "two thousand thirteen" (2013). It represents the year when the action or state began.</div><div><strong>wohnen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the German verb that means "to live", "to reside". In the sentence, it’s the main verb in the first-person plural present tense.</div><div><strong>wir</strong> This is the first-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "we" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>hier</strong> This is the German adverb for "here". It describes the location where the action of living is taking place.</div>','<h2>Die Schuhe von meinem Vater sind komisch.</h2><div><strong>Die</strong> This is the definite article in German, equivalent to "the" in English. It indicates that the following noun is specific and known to the speaker. "Die" is used here because "Schuhe" is plural.</div><div><strong>Schuhe</strong> This is the plural form of the German word "Schuh", which means "shoes" in English. It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>von</strong> This is a preposition meaning "from" or "of" in English. It is used to indicate possession, showing that the shoes belong to "meinem Vater".</div><div><strong>meinem</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in the dative case, meaning "my" in English. The use of the dative case indicates an indirect object, in this case, implying possession of the father. "Meinem" is masculine since it refers to "Vater" (father), which is a masculine noun.</div><div><strong>Vater</strong> This is the German word for "father". It is a masculine noun, and this is why the possessive pronoun "meinem" is also masculine.</div><div><strong>sind</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It links the subject "Schuhe" to the adjective "komisch".</div><div><strong>komisch</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "strange" or "weird" in English. When used after the verb "sein", it describes the condition or quality of the subject, in this case, the shoes.</div>','<h2>Die Wände vom Haus sind grün.</h2><div><strong>Die</strong> This is the definite article in German, equivalent to "the" in English. It is used here in the plural nominative case, referring to the subject of the sentence, which is "Wände" (walls).</div><div><strong>Wände</strong> This is the plural form of "Wand" in German, meaning "walls". It serves as the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>vom</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "von" (from) and the definite article "dem" (the), which together mean "from the" or "of the" in English. It is used here to denote possession or association.</div><div><strong>Haus</strong> This is a German noun meaning "house". It follows "vom", indicating that the walls belong to the house.</div><div><strong>sind</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It is used here to connect the subject "Wände" with the predicate "grün".</div><div><strong>grün</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "green". It describes the color of the walls mentioned earlier in the sentence and agrees in number and case with the plural subject "Wände".</div>','<h2>Die Vögel fressen die Kirschen von unserem Kirschbaum.</h2><div><strong>Die</strong> This is the definite article in German for the plural nominative case, equivalent to "the" in English. It precedes plural nouns and here it’s used for "Vögel" (birds).</div><div><strong>Vögel</strong> This is the plural form of the German word "Vogel", which means "bird". In this sentence, it is the subject, indicating that the birds are the ones performing the action.</div><div><strong>fressen</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "fressen", which is commonly used for animals and means "to eat". In this context, it’s saying what the birds are doing.</div><div><strong>die</strong> Again, this is the definite article in German for the plural accusative case. Here it’s used for "Kirschen" (cherries), which is the direct object of the verb "fressen".</div><div><strong>Kirschen</strong> This is the plural form of the German word "Kirsche", meaning "cherry". It’s the object in the sentence, indicating what the birds are eating.</div><div><strong>von</strong> This is a preposition in German that can mean "from" or "of". In this sentence, it’s used to indicate possession, showing from whom or what the cherries are being eaten.</div><div><strong>unserem</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in German in the dative case, masculine singular form, meaning "our". It is used here to show that the cherry tree belongs to the speaker and possibly others who are included in "our".</div><div><strong>Kirschbaum</strong> This is a compound noun in German, formed from "Kirsche" (cherry) and "Baum" (tree), meaning "cherry tree". It’s in the masculine singular form and is the object of the preposition "von", indicating the source of the cherries.</div>','<h2>Ich habe von meiner Mutter ein Buch bekommen.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>habe</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have". Here, it’s combined with "bekommen" to form the present perfect tense.</div><div><strong>von</strong> This is a preposition that is equivalent to "from" in English. It’s used here to indicate the source or giver in the sentence.</div><div><strong>meiner Mutter</strong> This phrase translates to "my mother" in English. "Meiner" is the feminine dative form of the possessive pronoun "mein", which inflects due to the preposition "von" that requires the dative case. "Mutter" is the noun "mother".</div><div><strong>ein Buch</strong> This phrase means "a book" in English. "Ein" is an indefinite article in the accusative case due to it being the direct object in the sentence. "Buch" is the noun "book".</div><div><strong>bekommen</strong> This is the main verb in the sentence meaning "to receive" or "to get" in English. It’s placed at the end of the sentence because in German subordinate clauses, the verb often comes last. It’s part of the predicate in the present perfect tense alongside "habe".</div>','<h2>Ich gehe zurBank.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>gehe</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "gehen", which means "to go". It indicates the action being performed by the subject.</div><div><strong>zur</strong> This is a contraction of "zu der" and is a prepositional phrase in German composed of "zu" (to) and the definite article "der" (the), used here with a feminine noun. "Zur" signifies movement towards a destination or a relation to a specific place. There is a typo in the original sentence – it should be "zur Bank", meaning "to the bank", with "Bank" being the feminine noun for "bank".</div><div><strong>Bank</strong> This is a German noun meaning "bank". It is the object of the prepositional phrase "zur". As mentioned, there should be a space between "zur" and "Bank" in the correct sentence.</div>','<h2>Wir fahren zu einem Hotel.</h2><div><strong>Wir</strong> This is the first-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "we" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>fahren</strong> This is the first-person plural present tense form of the verb "fahren", which means "to drive" or "to go". It indicates the action being performed by the subject.</div><div><strong>zu</strong> This is a German preposition that means "to" or "towards" when used with destinations. It’s used to indicate the direction of the action.</div><div><strong>einem</strong> This is the indefinite article in the dative case for masculine or neuter nouns, corresponding to "a" or "an" in English. It’s used here to precede the noun "Hotel".</div><div><strong>Hotel</strong> This is a German noun that maintains the same meaning as in English, referring to a place that provides paid lodging. It’s neuter and here it’s in the dative case due to the preposition "zu".</div>'];var defBonus = ['<h2>Sie wollen mit ihnen Geschäfte machen.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the German pronoun for "they" or the polite form of "you" (singular and plural). The context usually dictates its meaning; it’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>wollen</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the modal verb "wollen", which means "to want to" in English. In the polite form "Sie", it would be translated as "want to" or "would like to".</div><div><strong>mit</strong> This is a German preposition meaning "with". It is used here to indicate association or participation.</div><div><strong>ihnen</strong> This is the dative case of the third-person plural pronoun or the polite form singular "you", meaning "with them" or "with you (formal)".</div><div><strong>Geschäfte</strong> This is a German noun meaning "business(es)" in English. In its plural form, it is referring to commercial transactions or dealings.</div><div><strong>machen</strong> This is the German verb "to make" or "to do". It is in the infinitive form because it is used with the modal verb "wollen". In the sentence, it helps to express the idea of conducting business.</div>','<h2>Sie sind oft mit Ihrem Sohn gereist.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the formal second-person pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It can also mean "they" depending on context, but the verb form will clarify which one it is. In this sentence, due to verb conjugation, it refers to the formal "you".</div><div><strong>sind</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense or the formal second-person present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". In this sentence, it is combined with "gereist" to form the perfect tense, which describes a completed action in the past. Since "Sie" is used, "sind" denotes the formal second person.</div><div><strong>oft</strong> This is an adverb meaning "often". It indicates the frequency at which the action (traveling) was performed.</div><div><strong>mit</strong> This is a preposition meaning "with". It is used to indicate accompaniment or being in the company of someone.</div><div><strong>Ihrem</strong> This is a possessive pronoun that means "your" in English. It is the dative form of "Ihr", which is the formal second-person possessive pronoun, used to show ownership or relation to the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>Sohn</strong> This word means "son". It is a noun that refers to a male child in relation to their parents.</div><div><strong>gereist</strong> This is the past participle of the verb "reisen", which means "to travel". When combined with the auxiliary verb "sind", it forms the perfect tense, indicating that the action has been completed in the past.</div>','<h2>Du zeichnest mit einem grünen Stift.</h2><div><strong>Du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s informal and used when speaking to one person you know well.</div><div><strong>zeichnest</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the verb "zeichnen", which means "to draw". It tells what the subject (you) is doing.</div><div><strong>mit</strong> This is a German preposition that means "with". It’s used here to introduce the instrument or means by which the action of the verb is carried out.</div><div><strong>einem</strong> This is the masculine/neuter dative singular form of the indefinite article "ein", which means "a" or "an" in English. In the context of this sentence, it is used in the dative case because "mit" is a dative preposition.</div><div><strong>grünen</strong> This is the dative singular form of the adjective "grün", which means "green" in English. Adjectives in German take endings that agree in gender, number, and case with the noun they modify; in this case, it’s agreeing with "Stift" (pen) in the dative case.</div><div><strong>Stift</strong> This is a masculine noun that means "pen" in English. Here, it’s the object being used to draw and is in the dative case after the preposition "mit".</div>','<h2>Sie spielen mit gefälschten Pistolen.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the third-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "they" in English. It is used as the subject of the sentence. However, note that "Sie" can also mean "you" in the singular and plural formal form.</div><div><strong>spielen</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "spielen", which means "to play". It agrees with the subject "they" in this sentence.</div><div><strong>mit</strong> This is a German preposition meaning "with". It indicates that the action is being done in conjunction with something else, in this case, "gefälschten Pistolen".</div><div><strong>gefälschten</strong> This is the plural dative form of the past participle "gefälscht", which means "counterfeit" or "faked". It serves as an adjective in this sentence, modifying "Pistolen" (pistols).</div><div><strong>Pistolen</strong> This is the plural form of "Pistole", which means "pistol" in German. It’s the object of the preposition "mit", and together with "mit", it forms the phrase "with counterfeit pistols".</div>','<h2>Sie muss mit ihrer Kreditkarte bezahlen.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the third-person singular feminine pronoun in German, equivalent to "she" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>muss</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the modal verb "müssen", which means "must" or "to have to". It indicates obligation or necessity.</div><div><strong>mit</strong> This is a German preposition that translates to "with" in English. It’s used here to indicate the means by which the action of the sentence (paying) is to be carried out.</div><div><strong>ihrer</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in the dative case, feminine form, meaning "her". It indicates that the credit card belongs to the female subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>Kreditkarte</strong> This is a compound noun in German, which means "credit card". As a noun, it’s the object being used to perform the action of paying.</div><div><strong>bezahlen</strong> This is an infinitive verb in German meaning "to pay". The modal verb "muss" requires the main verb to be in its infinitive form at the end of the sentence.</div>','<h2>Jeden Tag gehe ich mit dir zur Schule.</h2><div><strong>Jeden Tag</strong> This is a German phrase meaning "every day". It indicates the frequency with which the action is performed.</div><div><strong>gehe</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "gehen", which means "to go". It describes the action performed by the subject.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>mit</strong> This is a German preposition that means "with" in English. It is used here to indicate the company in which the action is being performed.</div><div><strong>dir</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in the dative case in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It indicates the person with whom the subject is going to school.</div><div><strong>zur Schule</strong> This phrase combines the preposition "zu" (to) with the definite article "der" in the dative case ("der" becomes "der" due to contraction with "zu") and the noun "Schule" (school), resulting in "zur Schule", which means "to the school".</div>','<h2>Ihre Katze spielt mit einem Wollknäuel.</h2><div><strong>Ihre</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in German, meaning "your" in the formal form, or "her/their" depending on context. It indicates possession and agrees with the noun it describes in gender, number, and case. Here, it is feminine singular nominative, referring to "Katze" (cat).</div><div><strong>Katze</strong> This is a feminine noun in the nominative case, meaning "cat". It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>spielt</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "spielen", which means "to play". It describes the action that the subject (the cat) is doing.</div><div><strong>mit</strong> This is a preposition that means "with" in English. It is used here to introduce the object that the cat is playing with.</div><div><strong>einem</strong> This is an indefinite article in the dative case, masculine/neuter form, meaning "a" or "an". The noun it introduces ("Wollknäuel") is in the dative case due to the preposition "mit".</div><div><strong>Wollknäuel</strong> This is a neuter noun in the dative case, meaning "ball of wool" or "yarn ball". This is the object with which the cat is playing.</div>','<h2>Ich fange mit meiner Zunge Schneeflocken.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>fange</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "fangen", which means "to catch". It indicates the action that the subject is performing.</div><div><strong>mit</strong> This is a preposition in German which means "with" in English. It is used here to indicate the means by which the action is performed.</div><div><strong>meiner</strong> This is the feminine singular genitive case of the possessive pronoun "mein", which means "my" in English. It indicates possession and that the following noun "Zunge" is related to the subject "Ich".</div><div><strong>Zunge</strong> This is a feminine singular noun in German, which means "tongue" in English. It’s used here as the body part with which the subject catches something.</div><div><strong>Schneeflocken</strong> This is the plural form of the noun "Schneeflocke", which means "snowflakes" in English. It’s the direct object of the sentence, indicating what is being caught.</div>','<h2>Sofia singt das Lied mit den Zuschauern.</h2><div><strong>Sofia</strong> This is a proper noun, a female given name, serving as the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>singt</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "singen", which means "to sing". It indicates the action being performed by the subject.</div><div><strong>das Lied</strong> This phrase means "the song". "Das" is the neutral definite article "the", and "Lied" is a neutral noun meaning "song". Here, it functions as the direct object of the sentence, being the thing that is sung.</div><div><strong>mit</strong> This is a preposition which means "with". It introduces a prepositional phrase, indicating the manner or accompaniment of the action.</div><div><strong>den Zuschauern</strong> This phrase means "the audience" or "the spectators". "Den" is the plural definite article in the dative case, and "Zuschauern" is the dative plural form of "Zuschauer", which means "spectator" or "viewer". Together with "mit", this prepositional phrase means "with the audience/spectators".</div>','<h2>Wir reisten mit unserem Wohnwagen.</h2><div><strong>Wir</strong> This is the first-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "we" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>reisten</strong> This is the first-person plural past tense form of the verb "reisen", which means "to travel". It describes the action carried out by the subject.</div><div><strong>mit</strong> This is a preposition in German that means "with" in English. It’s used here to introduce the means or accompaniment.</div><div><strong>unserem</strong> This is the dative form of the possessive pronoun "unser", which means "our" in English. It modifies "Wohnwagen" to indicate possession, showing that the caravan belongs to the subject. In German, the possessive pronoun changes form to agree with the gender, number, and case of the noun it is describing.</div><div><strong>Wohnwagen</strong> This is a masculine noun in German meaning "caravan" or "travel trailer" in English. It’s the object of the preposition "mit" and is in the dative case due to the preposition.</div>','<h2>Ich werde dir mit deinen Hausaufgaben helfen.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>werde</strong> This is the first-person singular future tense auxiliary of the verb "werden", which is used to form the future tense in German. It implies that the action will take place in the future.</div><div><strong>dir</strong> This is the dative form of the second-person singular pronoun "du" in German, equivalent to "to you" or "for you" in English.</div><div><strong>mit</strong> This is a preposition in German that means "with" when describing accompanying with someone or something or when dealing with collaborative actions.</div><div><strong>deinen</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in the dative form, which is "your" in the context of masculine or plural nouns in English. It indicates that the homework belongs to the person being spoken to. The gender/number of the noun following determines the form of this possessive pronoun.</div><div><strong>Hausaufgaben</strong> This is a plural noun meaning "homework" in English. It is a compound noun made up of "Haus" (house) and "Aufgaben" (tasks).</div><div><strong>helfen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "to help" in German. It appears at the end of the clause because the German sentence structure often places the infinitive verb at the end, especially when used with modal verbs or in future tense constructions.</div>','<h2>Wir fahren mit unseren Kindern zur Schule.</h2><div><strong>Wir</strong> This is the first-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "we" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>fahren</strong> This is the first-person plural present tense form of the verb "fahren", which means "to drive", "to go", or "to travel". It indicates the action being performed by the subject.</div><div><strong>mit</strong> This is a preposition in German that can have various translations in English, such as "with" in this context. It is used to indicate accompaniment.</div><div><strong>unseren</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in the dative plural form, meaning "our". It modifies "Kindern" and shows possession or a relation to the subject.</div><div><strong>Kindern</strong> This is the dative plural form of the noun "Kind", which means "children". The noun is in the dative case because it is the indirect object of the sentence, following the preposition "mit".</div><div><strong>zur</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "zu" (to) and the definite article "der" in the dative singular feminine or neuter form. It translates as "to the" in English, and indicates direction or destination.</div><div><strong>Schule</strong> This is a noun meaning "school". It is feminine and in the dative case, following the preposition "zu". The phrase "zur Schule" means "to the school".</div>','<h2>Ihr lernt Deutsch mit diesem Programm.</h2><div><strong>Ihr</strong> This is the German second-person plural pronoun, equivalent to "you" in English when addressing more than one person. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>lernt</strong> This is the second-person plural present tense form of the verb "lernen", which means "to learn". It indicates the action being carried out by the subject.</div><div><strong>Deutsch</strong> This is a German noun meaning "German" [the language]. It’s the direct object of the sentence, indicating what is being learned.</div><div><strong>mit</strong> This is a German preposition meaning "with". It introduces the means by which the subject is learning German.</div><div><strong>diesem</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in the dative case meaning "this". It refers to the following noun, indicating a specific program.</div><div><strong>Programm</strong> This is a German noun meaning "program". It’s in the dative case because of the preposition "mit", and it describes the tool or method being used to learn German.</div>','<h2>Ja, wir haben viele von denen auf Lager.</h2><div><strong>Ja</strong> This is the German word for "yes". It is used to confirm or agree with something that has been said or asked.</div><div><strong>wir</strong> This is the first-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "we" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>haben</strong> This is the first-person plural present tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have". It indicates possession or existence of something in this context.</div><div><strong>viele</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "many". It describes the quantity of the noun that follows.</div><div><strong>von</strong> This is a German preposition that translates to "of" or "from". In this sentence, "von" is part of the phrase "von denen" which means "of those" or "of them".</div><div><strong>denen</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun in the dative plural form in German. It refers to previously mentioned items or items already understood by the speaker and listener.</div><div><strong>auf Lager</strong> This phrase means "in stock". "auf" is a preposition meaning "on" and "Lager" means "stock" or "inventory". Combined, they indicate that the items are available for sale or distribution.</div>','<h2>Du schlossest die Tür von deinem Auto.</h2><div><strong>Du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>schlossest</strong> This is the second-person singular past tense form of the verb "schließen", which means "to close". It indicates an action performed by the subject in the past.</div><div><strong>die Tür</strong> This phrase means "the door" in German. "Die" is the definite article in the feminine singular form, and "Tür" is the feminine noun for "door".</div><div><strong>von</strong> This is a preposition in German that can mean "from" or "of" in English, depending on the context. Here, it’s used to indicate possession.</div><div><strong>deinem</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in the dative case in German, meaning "your". It reflects the dative case because of the preposition "von", which requires the dative case. "Deinem" is the form used for neuter or masculine nouns in the singular when the owner is a male or where gender is not specified.</div><div><strong>Auto</strong> This is the neuter noun for "car" in German. It’s in the singular form and is the object of the prepositional phrase "von deinem Auto" (from your car).</div>','<h2>Es ist erschwinglich und von guter Qualität.</h2><div><strong>Es</strong> This is the German third-person neutral pronoun, equivalent to "it" in English.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It’s used here as the verb of the sentence, linking the subject to the predicates.</div><div><strong>erschwinglich</strong> This is a German adjective that means "affordable" or "within one’s means". It describes something that can be purchased without financial difficulty.</div><div><strong>und</strong> This is the German conjunction for "and". It connects the two attributive phrases in the sentence.</div><div><strong>von</strong> This is a German preposition that can mean "from" or "of", depending on the context. Here it’s used to indicate the origin or quality of something.</div><div><strong>guter</strong> This is the German adjective "gut" in its comparative form, meaning "good". It is declined in the genitive singular feminine or nominative/accusative singular neuter to match "Qualität", which is feminine singular.</div><div><strong>Qualität</strong> This is a German noun meaning "quality". It denotes the level of excellence of something.</div>','<h2>Nehmt mich in eure Gruppe von Freunden auf.</h2><div><strong>Nehmt</strong> This is the imperative form of "nehmen", which means "to take". It is used here as a command or request in the second-person plural, essentially saying "take me".</div><div><strong>mich</strong> This is the first-person singular accusative pronoun in German, equivalent to "me" in English. It’s the object of the sentence, the person being taken into the group.</div><div><strong>in</strong> This is a preposition that can mean "in" or "into" depending on the context. It indicates the direction towards which the action of the verb is directed, in this case into the group.</div><div><strong>eure</strong> This is the second-person plural possessive pronoun in the accusative case, meaning "your" (referring to belonging to more than one person). It describes ownership or association with the group.</div><div><strong>Gruppe</strong> This is a feminine noun meaning "group". In German, nouns are capitalized.</div><div><strong>von</strong> This is a common preposition meaning "from" or "of". Here it is used to express the "group of friends" construct.</div><div><strong>Freunden</strong> This is the plural form of "Freund", which means "friend". It is in the dative plural because "von" requires the dative case. The phrase "von Freunden" translates to "of friends".</div><div><strong>auf</strong> This is a separable verb prefix, which in this context, combined with "nehmen" (as in "aufnehmen"), means "to admit" or "to include". When the verb "nehmen" is used in sentences, the prefix often goes to the end.</div>','<h2>Ich habe sehr wenige Bilder von meiner Reise.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>habe</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have". It denotes possession or experience in this context.</div><div><strong>sehr</strong> This is an adverb meaning "very" in English. It is used here to intensify the adjective that follows.</div><div><strong>wenige</strong> This is an adjective meaning "few" in English. It describes the quantity of "Bilder" - the noun that follows it.</div><div><strong>Bilder</strong> This is a plural noun meaning "pictures" or "photos" in English. It is the direct object of the verb "habe", indicating what is possessed or experienced (here, taken on the trip).</div><div><strong>von</strong> This is a preposition meaning "of" or "from" in English. It introduces the phrase that tells where the pictures are from.</div><div><strong>meiner</strong> This is a possessive pronoun meaning "my" in English. It is in the dative case here because it is used with the preposition "von", which dictates the dative case for the object that follows.</div><div><strong>Reise</strong> This is a singular noun meaning "trip" or "journey" in English. It is used here in the dative case as the object of the preposition "von" (indicated by "meiner") to express ownership or relation to the pictures.</div>','<h2>Wir haben uns in den Straßen von München verlaufen.</h2><div><strong>Wir</strong> This is the first-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "we" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>haben</strong> This is the first-person plural present tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have". It’s used here as the auxiliary verb for the compound past tense, known as the Perfekt tense.</div><div><strong>uns</strong> This is a reflexive pronoun in the accusative case, which refers back to the subject "wir". In German, many verbs are reflexive, which means the action is being done to the subject itself. In this case, it indicates that "we" are the ones who got lost.</div><div><strong>in</strong> This is a preposition which can mean "in" or "into" in English, depending on the context. It indicates the location where the action of getting lost took place.</div><div><strong>den Straßen</strong> This phrase means "the streets" in English. "Straßen" is the plural form of "Straße" (street), and "den" is the definite article in the dative plural, used here after the preposition "in" which requires the dative case when indicating a static location.</div><div><strong>von</strong> This is another preposition, which means "from" or "of" in English. It indicates belonging or origin.</div><div><strong>München</strong> This is the German name for Munich, a city in Germany. It is a proper noun used here to indicate the specific location where they got lost.</div><div><strong>verlaufen</strong> This is the past participle of the verb "sich verlaufen", which means "to get lost". It implies an action was completed in the past, and because it is used with the auxiliary verb "haben", it indicates a past experience or event.</div>','<h2>Ach was! Ist das weit von hier?</h2><div><strong>Ach</strong> This is an interjection in German often used to express a range of emotions such as surprise, disbelief, or mild annoyance. Here, it could translate as "Oh" or "Really" in an English context.</div><div><strong>was</strong> This is the German word for "what". In the context of the interjection "Ach was!", it is part of a common expression that might be similar to saying "Oh really?" or "Is that so?" in English.</div><div><strong>Ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It corresponds to "is" in this context.</div><div><strong>das</strong> This is a neuter demonstrative pronoun or article in German, meaning "that" or "this" in English, depending on the context. Here, it is functioning as a demonstrative pronoun referring to something previously mentioned or understood in the conversation.</div><div><strong>weit</strong> This is an adjective in German meaning "far" in English. Used in a question, it is asking about the distance.</div><div><strong>von hier</strong> This phrase literally translates to "from here" in English, with "von" meaning "from" and "hier" meaning "here". It asks about the proximity or distance of something relative to the speaker’s current location.</div>','<h2>Normalerweise von neun bis fünf.</h2><div><strong>Normalerweise</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "usually" or "normally". It sets the context for a typical or standard situation or time frame.</div><div><strong>von</strong> This is a German preposition that translates to "from" in English. It indicates the start of a time period or range when used in this context.</div><div><strong>neun</strong> This is the number "nine" in German. In the context of time, it refers to 9 o’clock.</div><div><strong>bis</strong> This is another German preposition that means "to" or "until" in English. It indicates the end of a time period or range.</div><div><strong>fünf</strong> This is the number "five" in German. As with "neun", it pertains to time and refers to 5 o’clock. In the context of the given phrase, it’s used to denote the end of a standard workday.</div>','<h2>Nein, es ist ziemlich nah von hier.</h2><div><strong>Nein</strong> This is the German word for "no". It is used to negate a statement or respond negatively to a question.</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is the third-person singular neuter pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It indicates the state of being or existence.</div><div><strong>ziemlich</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "quite" or "rather" in English, used here to modify the adjective that follows.</div><div><strong>nah</strong> This is an adjective in German that means "close" or "near" in English. In this sentence, it’s used to describe the proximity of something.</div><div><strong>von hier</strong> This phrase combines the preposition "von", which translates to "from", with the pronoun "hier", meaning "here". Together, they indicate the origin of the proximity, meaning "from here".</div>','<h2>Der Schnee fiel von den Bäumen.</h2><div><strong>Der</strong> This is the definite article in German for masculine nominative singular nouns. It translates to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>Schnee</strong> This is a masculine singular noun in German, meaning "snow". It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>fiel</strong> This is the third-person singular past tense form of the verb "fallen", which means "to fall". It indicates that the action happened in the past.</div><div><strong>von</strong> This is a preposition in German that can mean "from" or "off" depending on the context. In this sentence, it means "from" indicating the origin or source.</div><div><strong>den</strong> This is the definite article in German for plural nouns in the dative case. It translates to "the" in English.</div><div><strong>Bäumen</strong> This is the plural dative form of the noun "Baum", meaning "trees". After the preposition "von", which requires the dative case, "Baum" changes to "Bäumen".</div>','<h2>Frühstück gibt es von acht bis elf Uhr.</h2><div><strong>Frühstück</strong> This is the German word for "breakfast". It refers to the first meal of the day.</div><div><strong>gibt es</strong> This comes from the German verb "geben", which means "to give", combined with "es" for "there is/are". Together, "gibt es" translates to "there is" or "is available/offered".</div><div><strong>von</strong> This is a German preposition meaning "from". It indicates the start of a time range.</div><div><strong>acht</strong> This is the German word for "eight". It denotes the start time for the breakfast offering.</div><div><strong>bis</strong> This is a German conjunction/preposition meaning "until". It marks the end of a time range.</div><div><strong>elf</strong> This is the German word for "eleven". It denotes the end time for the breakfast offering.</div><div><strong>Uhr</strong> This is the German word for "o’clock" or "hour", used to specify time.</div>','<h2>Sie ist von sehr weit gekommen, um das zu sehen.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "she" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". In this context, it’s used to form the present perfect tense in combination with "gekommen", which is the past participle of "kommen" (to come).</div><div><strong>von</strong> This is a preposition that can mean "from" or "of". In this sentence, it’s used to indicate the starting point of the action – "from".</div><div><strong>sehr weit</strong> This is a phrase combining "sehr" (very) and "weit" (far). It describes the extent of the distance, indicating she has come from a place that is very far away.</div><div><strong>gekommen</strong> This is the past participle of the verb "kommen", which means "to come". The past participle is used here with "ist" to form the present perfect tense, which describes an action that has been completed.</div><div><strong>um</strong> This is a conjunction that introduces a purpose or a goal. It is equivalent to "in order to" or "to" in English.</div><div><strong>das</strong> This is a demonstrative pronoun that means "that". It is used here to refer to something specific that she has come to see.</div><div><strong>zu sehen</strong> This is the infinitive form of "sehen", which means "to see". With "um", it indicates the purpose of her coming — to see something.</div>','<h2>Die Polizeistation ist nicht weit von hier.</h2><div><strong>Die</strong> This is the definite article in German for feminine and plural nouns in the nominative case, equivalent to "the" in English. It indicates a specific item or concept.</div><div><strong>Polizeistation</strong> This is a compound noun in German. "Polizei" means "police", and "Station" translates to "station", so together they mean "police station".</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be". It describes the state or existence of the subject.</div><div><strong>nicht</strong> This is the German word for "not". It negates the statement that follows, thus "is not" when paired with "ist".</div><div><strong>weit</strong> This means "far" in German. It is an adjective describing distance.</div><div><strong>von</strong> This is a preposition in German that can mean various things depending on context. In this sentence, it means "from".</div><div><strong>hier</strong> This means "here" in English. It indicates the current location of the speaker or the location being referred to in the conversation.</div>','<h2>Ich fuhr zu meinem Freund.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>fuhr</strong> This is the first-person singular past tense form of the verb "fahren", which means "to drive" or "to travel". In this sentence, it indicates a completed action in the past.</div><div><strong>zu</strong> This is a preposition that can mean "to" or "towards" in English. It’s used to indicate direction or destination.</div><div><strong>meinem</strong> This is the dative form of the possessive pronoun "mein" (my), used here to indicate possession or association with the subject "Ich" (I). The dative case is used after the preposition "zu" to indicate the indirect object – in this case, "Freund" (friend).</div><div><strong>Freund</strong> This is a German noun that means "friend". In this sentence, it’s the destination of the subject’s travel. It is in the masculine singular form and is the object of the preposition "zu".</div>','<h2>Wenn sie ein Auto hätte, würde sie zu mir nach Hause kommen.</h2><div><strong>Wenn</strong> This is a German conjunction meaning "if". It introduces a conditional clause that specifies a condition that could trigger the action mentioned in the main clause.</div><div><strong>sie</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "she" in English. In this sentence, it is the subject of the conditional clause.</div><div><strong>ein Auto</strong> This means "a car". It is a combination of an indefinite article "ein" and the noun "Auto", which describes the object that the subject would have.</div><div><strong>hätte</strong> This is the third-person singular subjunctive form of the verb "haben", which means "to have". In the context of this sentence, it is used to express a hypothetical situation - that she would have a car.</div><div><strong>würde</strong> This is the conditional form of the verb "werden" used to form the conditional mood in German. Here it indicates what she "would do" in the hypothetical situation.</div><div><strong>sie</strong> This is again the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "she" in English. It is the subject of the main clause this time.</div><div><strong>zu mir</strong> This means "to me". It is a prepositional phrase where "zu" translates to "to" and "mir" is the first-person singular pronoun in the dative case, equivalent to "me" in English.</div><div><strong>nach Hause</strong> This phrase translates as "home" or "to the house". "nach" is a preposition that can mean "to", and "Hause" is a special form of the noun "Haus", meaning "house", used after certain prepositions.</div><div><strong>kommen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "kommen", which means "to come". It follows "würde" to form the conditional mood - indicating the action she would perform if the condition were fulfilled.</div>','<h2>Ich mag zur Party kommen.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>mag</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "mögen", which means "to like" or "to enjoy". In this context, it conveys a desire or preference to do something.</div><div><strong>zur</strong> This is a contraction of "zu der" in German, which translates to "to the" in English. "Zu" is a preposition that can mean "to" or "towards", and "der" is the definite article for feminine or plural nouns in the dative case. "Party" is a feminine noun adopted from English into German, and when used with the preposition "zu", it becomes "zur Party".</div><div><strong>Party</strong> This is a German noun borrowed from English, meaning "party". It retains the same meaning as in English, referring to a social event or gathering. In German, "Party" is a feminine noun, hence it is combined with "zur" in the dative case when preceded by the preposition "zu".</div><div><strong>kommen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "kommen", which means "to come" in English. In this sentence, it is used at the end to indicate the action that the subject wants to perform.</div>','<h2>Ich fahre zur Arbeit mit meinem alten Auto.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>fahre</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "fahren", which means "to drive". It denotes the action that the subject is undertaking.</div><div><strong>zur Arbeit</strong> This is a fixed prepositional phrase consisting of "zu" (to) and "der Arbeit" (the work). The preposition "zu" contracts with the definite article "der" to form "zur". It indicates the destination of the drive, which is "to work".</div><div><strong>mit</strong> This is a preposition that means "with" in English. It is used here to introduce the means by which the subject is going to drive to work.</div><div><strong>meinem</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in dative case, masculine singular form, which means "my" in English. It indicates that the noun it describes belongs to the speaker.</div><div><strong>alten</strong> This is an adjective meaning "old". It describes the noun "Auto" that follows, and agrees with it in terms of case, number, and gender.</div><div><strong>Auto</strong> This is a neuter noun meaning "car". It is the object associated with the preposition "mit" and is the means by which the subject goes to work. In combination with the previous elements, it forms the phrase "with my old car".</div>','<h2>Jeden Tag gehe ich mit dir zur Schule.</h2><div><strong>Jeden Tag</strong> This is a German phrase meaning "every day". It’s an expression of time frequency and sets the scene for a habitual action.</div><div><strong>gehe</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "gehen", which means "to go". It indicates the action performed by the subject in the sentence.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence who is performing the action.</div><div><strong>mit dir</strong> This phrase in German means "with you". "mit" is the preposition "with", and "dir" is the dative form of the second-person singular pronoun, "du", used here to indicate the company or the person accompanying the subject.</div><div><strong>zur Schule</strong> This is a combination of "zu der Schule" in German and means "to school". "zu" is a preposition that can mean "to" or "towards", while "der" (contracted to "zur" when used with "zu") is the definite article "the" in the feminine or dative case, and "Schule" is the noun "school".</div>','<h2>Sie werden auch nicht zur Arbeit gehen.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the German personal pronoun in the third-person plural or formal second-person singular, equivalent to "they" or "you" (formal) in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>werden</strong> This is a German auxiliary verb used to form the future tense or to express a likelihood or possibility, akin to "will" in English.</div><div><strong>auch</strong> This is the German word for "also" or "too". It is used to add information to the sentence, indicating that what is being stated is in addition to something else.</div><div><strong>nicht</strong> This is the German word for "not". It is used to negate a statement or verb.</div><div><strong>zur Arbeit</strong> This is a prepositional phrase where "zur" is a contraction of "zu der" meaning "to the" in English, and "Arbeit" means "work". Together, "zur Arbeit" means "to work".</div><div><strong>gehen</strong> This is the German verb for "to go". Here it’s the infinitive form used alongside the auxiliary verb "werden" to construct the future tense.</div>'];definitions = definitions.concat(defBonus);